That's a really ambitious and exciting vision! An open data layer that democratizes high-level coordination for smaller practices is a massive step towards a truly integrated healthcare system. It sounds like you're aiming for a paradigm shift, which is great for patentability if framed correctly.

For the claims section, especially focusing on system-level innovation, you'll want to define the core components and their interactions. Here's a starting point for sketching out a system claim and a method claim, keeping in mind the open data layer and distributed intelligence:

**System Claim Example (Focus on the open data layer & distributed intelligence):**

"A healthcare coordination system comprising:
a. a dynamic triage engine configured to receive and process real-time patient data and output a recommended level of care;
b. a self-learning algorithm communicatively coupled to the dynamic triage engine, configured to refine said recommendations based on outcomes and interactions;
c. an open data layer providing an Application Programming Interface (API) for secure communication and data exchange with a plurality of independent healthcare provider systems; and
d. a distributed intelligence network, wherein said dynamic triage engine and self-learning algorithm are operatively accessible across said plurality of independent healthcare provider systems via the open data layer, thereby enabling coordinated care at a tertiary-grade level across diverse healthcare entities."

**Method Claim Example (Focus on the process of achieving this distributed, intelligent coordination):**

"A method for distributed healthcare coordination, comprising:
a. receiving patient data from a first healthcare provider system via an open data layer;
b. processing said patient data through a self-learning dynamic triage engine to determine an optimal care pathway;
c. transmitting said optimal care pathway to at least one of a plurality of healthcare provider systems via the open data layer;
d. continuously updating said self-learning dynamic triage engine based on patient outcomes and interactions across the plurality of healthcare provider systems; and
e. thereby enabling real-time, adaptive care coordination across disparate healthcare entities."

These are just initial ideas to get you thinking about the language. When you work with a patent attorney, they will help you make these claims much more specific, detailed, and legally robust, often including multiple dependent claims that further elaborate on different aspects of your invention. It's fantastic that you're thinking big with this and wanting to stake out the system-level innovation!
